My non-negotiables in Ireland:

🏔️Visit the tombs at Knowth
🌈 See the colorful homes of Cobh
🐑 Go on my own baby lamb tour 🥹

(TW: mental health.) I was not supposed to come to Ireland originally. The truth is, my depression has consumed me to the point where I felt like/ was ready to give up these last 2 months. I found myself crying most hours of the day, not being able to eat or get myself up out of bed, and struggling to be happy even though there was so much GOOD around me. I prayed so hard every day that my mental health would get better. I was taking all the right steps. However, the sad reality is that mental health (a lot of the time) is not a quick fix. 

I grew up learning about Ireland from my mom when she came here 30 years ago. She got an opportunity to speak here for her job. She didn’t want to leave me in Pittsburgh for 10 days where she wouldn’t have service to communicate with me, so she brought me on this trip with her. The reality of my mental health is: I’ve cried most days I’ve been here. However, this trip has STILL been the most meaningful and important trip of my life. 

Although I am struggling, I find so much beauty in the fact that maybe sharing my struggles may help one of you feel less alone and okay with being imperfect (as we all are.) This is a reminder to never compare yourself to the “perfect” lives you see on social media. Because we are ALL human, and we are ALL imperfect no matter how aesthetic our lives may appear on Instagram.
